<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the FOUR `sys_choice` rows that
    enumerate the legal values of the `priority` Choice field on the
    `x_casemgmt_case` custom table inside the scoped application
    `x_casemgmt`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim):
        Field      Type     Constraints
        priority   Choice   Low, Medium, High, Critical

    Per AAP Section 0.4.1 (Refactored Structure Planning):
        choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml -> Low, Medium, High, Critical

    Per the assigned-folder description and AAP Section 0.4.1, new cases
    default to `Medium` priority - a sensible mid-range default for case
    management. The default itself is configured in the parent dictionary
    entry (../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_priority.xml has
    <default_value>Medium</default_value>); these sys_choice records merely
    enumerate the allowed values without preferring any one of them at the
    Choice-list level. The Choice-list `<sequence>` controls dropdown DISPLAY
    order, NOT default selection - displaying Low first does not change the
    fact that Medium is auto-applied at insert time when no explicit value
    is provided.

    The values authored here are the EXHAUSTIVE, CLOSED enumeration that the
    AAP mandates - exactly four records, no more and no fewer. Per the
    MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE in AAP Section 0.7.2, additional priority levels
    such as `Urgent`, `Severe`, `Emergency`, `None`, `Trivial`, etc. are
    explicitly out of scope for this POC. The increment-of-100 sequence
    spacing leaves room for future extensibility without renumbering, but
    no extension is authorized in this build.

    Per AAP Sections 0.5.2 and 0.4.1, the labels declared here are read by:

      The parent dictionary entry that declares this field as Choice:
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_priority.xml
            (mandatory=true, choice=3 means "Choice list - dropdown only";
            default_value=Medium picks one of the four labels declared
            below as the auto-applied value at insert time.)

      The Manager View dashboard's "All cases by priority" bar chart:
        ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_priority.xml
            (bar grouped by priority - four bars, one per label below.
            The visual ordering of the bars is driven by the `sequence`
            field declared here: Low (left) -> Medium -> High -> Critical
            (right). This gives the dashboard a meaningful "left-to-right
            urgency" visualization that internal users intuitively grasp.)

      The synthetic demo cases satisfying AAP Section 0.4.1 minimum-data
      threshold (each demo case picks one of these four values to exercise
      the Manager View bar chart and demonstrate Choice-field behavior on
      the internal form):
        ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_01.xml ... _demo_10.xml

    The Experience Portal submission widget per AAP Section 0.4.4 does NOT
    expose this field to anonymous external requesters - per AAP Section
    0.7.4, the public submission form has only five inputs: subject, type,
    description, requester_name, requester_email. The `priority` field is
    populated by the parent dictionary entry's <default_value>Medium</default_value>
    server-side at insert time. Internal users (case_manager or assigned
    case_agent) can re-prioritize a case after creation through the standard
    form view as new information emerges (e.g., a Low-priority complaint
    that escalates to Critical when additional facts surface). The Experience
    Portal lookup widget likewise does NOT expose this field per AAP Section
    0.7.4 ("the lookup page returns ONLY status, subject, opened_date - no
    internal fields exposed").

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 178-179:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_priority")
            private String priority;
        ArkCase's `priority` was a free-form `String` JPA column with NO
        platform-level enumeration check. Any caller could assign any
        arbitrary string ("urgent", "URGENT", "URG", "p1", "P1", "Hi",
        "HIGH!!!", "rush", etc.) and the JPA layer enforced no validation.
        This made aggregate analytics (e.g., "count of high-priority cases")
        unreliable across ArkCase deployments because the priority column
        accumulated typos, casing variants, and ad-hoc free-text from the
        Frevvo form, the Activiti workflow side-channel, and direct SQL
        scripts. The ServiceNow target FIXES this by declaring a controlled
        vocabulary of EXACTLY four labels here, enforced at platform-
        validation time through the parent dictionary entry's
        `<choice>3</choice>` setting in
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_priority.xml. Every case insert from
        any path (internal form, Table API, scripted REST, seed scripts)
        is now guaranteed to land on one of the four labels below or be
        rejected.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFileConstants.java does
        NOT declare a priority enumeration; it only declares OBJECT_TYPE,
        EVENT_TYPE_*, and queue-action constants. The priority enumeration
        was therefore implicit / undocumented in ArkCase - the target
        FIXES that defect by declaring the four values here explicitly.
      - The four AAP-mandated values (`Low`, `Medium`, `High`, `Critical`)
        are standard ITSM/case-management priority levels matching the
        OOB ServiceNow `incident.priority` and `change_request.priority`
        conventions. They are entirely defined by the AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim, not derived from any specific ArkCase code path.
      - The field name is `priority` (lowercase, 8 chars; NOT `casePriority`
        as in the ArkCase Java field name, NOT `case_priority` as in the
        ArkCase MySQL column name `cm_case_priority`) per AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim. This matches the conventional ServiceNow Choice-field
        naming convention across the platform.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - EXACTLY four records: no fewer, no more. Per AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim. The four records below are the COMPLETE enumeration.
      - Title Case labels: `Low`, `Medium`, `High`, `Critical`. NOT
        uppercase (ArkCase legacy convention may have used "HIGH"), NOT
        lowercase, NOT camelCase. The agent prompt's Phase 3 verbatim:
        "All four labels are Title Case, single words. No spaces, no
        hyphens, no special characters." Each label is a single ASCII
        word with the first letter capitalized.
      - Label = Value pattern: each `<value>` matches its sibling
        `<label>` byte-for-byte. The stored value IS the human-readable
        label - no integer priority codes, no enum ordinals, no separate
        machine-key. This matches the pattern used by sibling Choice
        lists in this app (sys_choice_case_status, sys_choice_case_type,
        sys_choice_case_task_status, sys_choice_case_task_type,
        sys_choice_case_pending_reason, sys_choice_case_party_party_type)
        and is essential for the Manager View bar chart aggregation
        (GlideAggregate groupBy('priority')) to produce coherent labels
        without translation.
      - Sequence ordering by ascending urgency in increments of 100:
            Low (100) -> Medium (200) -> High (300) -> Critical (400)
        This is the standard "ascending urgency" convention. Per the
        agent prompt's Key Insight #3, this order is intentional:
            (a) the dropdown order on the case form (least urgent first
                so an agent triaging a new case sees Low at the top and
                escalates from there - prevents accidental Critical-by-
                default-cursor-position)
            (b) the bar order on the Manager View "All cases by priority"
                bar chart (../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_priority.xml)
                left-to-right: Low to Critical, giving a meaningful visual
                gradient from least to most urgent.
            (c) the future extensibility - increment-of-100 spacing leaves
                room for inserting new values (e.g., Urgent at sequence
                350 between High and Critical) without renumbering existing
                rows, though the AAP MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE prohibits
                adding any in this POC.
        Per the agent prompt's Key Insight #3 verbatim: "NEVER use the
        alphabetical order (Critical -> High -> Low -> Medium)." The
        ascending-urgency order is non-negotiable.
      - All four records are <inactive>false</inactive>: every value is
        active and selectable in the dropdown. There are no deprecated
        legacy values to filter out (this is a greenfield Choice list).
      - No <dependent_value/>: priority is a TOP-LEVEL classification
        whose legal values do NOT depend on `status`, `type`, or any
        other field. A Draft case can be Critical; a Closed case can be
        Low; a General Inquiry can be Critical (e.g., a high-profile
        public-records request); a Complaint can be Low (e.g., a minor
        suggestion). No cascading dropdown is needed.
      - No <hint/>: the labels are self-documenting (Low, Medium, High,
        Critical are universally understood urgency terms). The agent
        prompt explicitly suppresses helper text per the POC scope.
      - No default value at this Choice level: per AAP Section 0.4.1 and
        the agent prompt's Phase 4 verbatim, the default is configured
        in the DICTIONARY entry (../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_priority.xml
        has <default_value>Medium</default_value>), NOT in the choice
        records here. The choice records merely define the available
        options; the dictionary picks which one is auto-applied at insert
        time. This separation is the standard ServiceNow design pattern -
        making the default a property of the COLUMN (one default per
        column) rather than a property of the VALUE (which would require
        a "default" flag on each choice with at-most-one constraint).
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every record's `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` resolve into the `x_casemgmt`
        scoped application by `source` attribute lookup. NO global-scope
        writes - the OOB tables sys_user, sys_user_group, sys_user_role,
        core_company, task, incident, etc. are never modified. The
        OOB `incident.priority` Choice values (1-Critical, 2-High,
        3-Moderate, 4-Low, 5-Planning) are NOT touched - this scoped
        Choice list is independent.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_casemgmt`), not by literal sys_id. Each
        record's `<sys_id>` element value is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key - computed as MD5 of the canonical
        identifier `x_casemgmt_case.priority.<Value>` so that re-generation
        of this XML yields byte-identical output (no random UUIDs). The
        sys_id is NOT a reference to any other record. The MD5 inputs
        are documented in the trailing comment block below for full
        traceability.
      - The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention; ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the scope id is concrete in the XML before export, which the import process resolves into the final
        scope namespace.
      - English language only: `<language>en</language>` on every record
        per the POC scope. The platform supports localization via
        additional sys_choice records keyed by `language`, but no
        non-English locales are in scope.
      - `<sys_domain>global</sys_domain>` on every record: domain
        separation is not used by this scoped application.
      - No PII: the labels are categorical urgency terms only; no real
        names, email addresses, or organizational identifiers are
        derived from or stored in these records.
      - No smart quotes, no leading/trailing whitespace, no BOM. Strict
        XML conformance for ServiceNow Update Set re-import preview.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped application)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record)
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml (parent table; priority field's host)
        - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_priority.xml (parent dictionary entry;
          declares the column shape, choice=3, default_value=Medium,
          mandatory=true. Without this entry the sys_choice records below
          have no column to attach to.)

      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD BEFORE:
        - ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_priority.xml
            (Manager View bar chart grouped by priority - four bars, one
            per label below, ordered Low -> Medium -> High -> Critical
            left-to-right via the sequence values declared here)
        - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_*.xml
            (demo cases set this field; values must match the labels here
            byte-for-byte for the GlideRecord seed lookups by `number` to
            populate the priority field correctly. The demo cases SHOULD
            distribute across all four priority values to exercise the
            Manager View bar chart, though the AAP does not mandate
            specific per-case priority assignments.)

      Loading order is enforced by the alphabetical Update Set preview
      ordering plus the record-by-record dependency-resolution pass.

    The MD5 input for each record's <sys_id> is the canonical identifier
    <table>.<element>.<value>, matching the convention used by the
    sibling Choice files (sys_choice_case_status.xml,
    sys_choice_case_type.xml, sys_choice_case_task_status.xml,
    sys_choice_case_party_party_type.xml):
        MD5("x_casemgmt_case.priority.Low")      = 6224e4afe120474dd8d1257b4a406d37
        MD5("x_casemgmt_case.priority.Medium")   = 7cdfc33aa8fe789423d712565ee468bc
        MD5("x_casemgmt_case.priority.High")     = d7ca8d1e5a898400629bddebe06a9824
        MD5("x_casemgmt_case.priority.Critical") = 34a378616cc6fe411402335b0c0243da
    These hashes are recomputable from the AAP-mandated canonical input,
    guaranteeing deterministic XML re-generation across all build runs and
    idempotent re-imports on any fresh PDI without sys_id collisions.
-->
